Hout Bay, also known as the Republic of [http://www.houtbay.info Hout Bay], is a beautiful bay on the Atlantic coast about 15 minutes drive from [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]].<br>
The first written account of Hout Bay was in 1614 by the English East India Company's Master's Mate on board a ship called "Gift". Hout Bay was, however, only named in 1653 when [[Van Riebeeck]] visited Hout bay for the first time in July of that year. A diary entry records that he saw “the finest forest in the world". It was Jan Van Riebeeck who eventually named Hout Bay when he wrote in his diary in November 1652 of t’houtaeit jien.